task.summary: Default task
June 19th, 2015 - analyze_string.py added to the pdb_data_mining package - Several bugs remain in some of the code of the files in the pdb_data_mining package
June 22nd, 2015 - Finished download_ftp.py, parse_xml.py, manage_sql.py... all are in working order

June 23rd, 2015 - Successfully downloaded the XML files and extracted important information to be stored into the database - Working on inserting rows of sorted data into the database - Working on designing natural language processing to discern the most commonly utilized chemicals in the growth of these protein crystals

June 23rd, 2015 - Successfully stored all sorted data into the database file contained in "Database" directory - Successfully applied the first set of string processing algorithms to the sorted data's crystallization information - Continuing to redesign string processing algorithms to produce a fuller and more exactly representative list of all of the chemicals used in the crystallization of these protein structures, as well as their respective concentrations
June 23rd, 2015 - Updated the analyze_details file in pdb_data_analysis
June 27th, 2015 - Fixed file path to information.db so that data can be successfully stored in the in the database following the parsing step

June 29th, 2015 - Fixed regex commands and added string processing commands in analyze_details.py to produce the names of chemicals used to crystallize the protein and their respective concentrations - Cleaned up the project files a bit
June 29th, 2015 - All sorts of things are wrong, most problems with regex and other text-processing-related code have been solved. - The database code is a mess and it does not work either
June 30th, 2015 - Many things have been fixed - Creating several new data tables storing various interesting sets of information regarding chemicals used in the crystallization of the proteins

July 7th, 2015 - Tons of changes, the logic behind the project has changed in a big way - Most changes can be viewed by comparing parse_details.py (the new logical approach) and analyze_details.py (the old logical approach) - Things are much better now, the golden reference will soon truly be a complete, untainted list of chemical names to work with from here on out

July 8th, 2015 - Tons of changes, the logic behind the project has changed in a big way - Things are much better now, the golden reference is now a complete, untainted list of chemical names to work with from here on out - All language filters are applied in the one function that creates the golden reference list through a series of for loops, while loops, if/else statements - Need to comment regex and key functions in parse_details.py... rather unreadable right now (especially the regex commands)

July 14th, 2015 - Cleaned up pdb_data_analysis directory - Cleaned up manage_sql.py - Added a third table, "golden_chemical_reference" to store only serviceable chemical names - Updated code flow in main.py - TO-DO: Create entry_data successfully, must rerun main.py as it is right now

July 15th, 2015 - Fixed a whole ton of code - Currently testing SQL queries that may replace cumbersome searching code in query_entries.py - Still in the works of testing the download of full XML files that contain the atom coordinates for those structures that were crystallized with those chemicals that we are interested in - Still in the works of organizing tables within the database and joining rows that have some relationship to each other across tables - Entry_data table seems to have been filled properly with the expect 50,000+ values
July 16th, 2015 - Possibly close to finishing query_entries.py

July 16th, 2015 - Query_entries.py is still in the works, making significant progress. Held up on UPDATE and SELECT. Index never passes 0. Values are still never updated from their original names to the standard name

July 17th, 2015 - All SQL queries were made to work in query_entries.py. - Issues with SQL queries include that other names (not delimited properly) are ignored by the query, this problem was fixed with the original code so main.py has been reverted to use original search. - All full .xml files have been downloaded from the FTP site so that the number of salt bridges may be calculated now.

July 20th, 2015 - Making all of the code work as of now. Once it works, will being perfecting it and finishing it for sure. - Experimenting with XPATHs in parse_xml.py to extract only those particular attributes that match the values I am looking for (i.e., correct chain ID, residual ID, and atom ID)

July 21st, 2015 - Most of the XML parsing is brute force and requires cleaning up before it can truly be called a finished product - However, all of the code works. All important data has been transferred into comma-delimited files and is ready for analysis in MATLAB
July 31st, 2015 - Huge fixes - Major clean-up - Writing down important values for use in final paper, talk, and presentation
